{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"alias":"nutbrown-catatonic-whale","description":"## Why\nThe pattern only pays off if future sessions can discover and reuse it. A first-class doc is\nhow the next agent adds an ensure correctly and understands the invariants (esp. that the\nmarker gates the hint, never the repair) and the A-tier future.\n\n## What\nWrite `docs/migrations.md`: how to add an ensure unit (append to the `ensures.py` registry\nwith a stable id + a check-then-act callable; bump a co-located id only for a behavior change);\nthe entry points (init/re-init, `fsck --fix`, server startup — all reconcile unconditionally);\nthe applied-set marker + the 24h-rate-limited write-path hint; the marker-gates-hint-never-repair\ninvariant; the hot-path performance contract (≤1 read/process, no sweep on writes); and the\nA-tier future (committed store-format version + ordered ledger, fail-closed on too-new) with the\ncommitted-version recommendation. Use gc-config as the reference example.\n\n## Scope\nIn: `docs/migrations.md` + a link from the docs index/CLAUDE.md. Out: code (WS1-3), tests (WS5).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `docs/migrations.md` documents adding an ensure unit (registry + stable id + check-then-act) with gc-config as the worked reference\n- [ ] Documents the entry points, the applied-set marker, the rate-limited write-path hint, and the marker-gates-hint-never-repair invariant\n- [ ] Documents the hot-path performance contract (no sweep on writes; ≤1 marker read/process)\n- [ ] Captures A-tier future (committed store-format version + ordered ledger, fail-closed on too-new) + the committed-version recommendation","id":"68e1-5dbc-732c-4cd3","parent_id":"9ccb-27ee-24dd-4944","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"WS4: docs/migrations.md — first-class ensure-pattern reuse guide"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783569044591436001,"uuid":"789c8f23-dcf9-4b50-b1e7-217630783a4c"}